<br>
The price of anything, whether it be a player made item, a dropped item, or tradeskill supply is what people are willing to pay for it.  That price is a function of supply and demand.  Lots of factors influence both the supply and the demand, and the market takes all of these into consideration.  Fairness has nothing to do with it.<br>
<br>
Lets look at one recent example, tae ew blood.  Farming tae ew blood requires a group of 50 plus characters, or a single pretty high level soloer, and its time consuming.  How much is a drop of tae ew blood worth? <br>
<br>
Well, the price of the tae ew blood is determined by the value of the end products.  Tae ew chain and tae ew weapons are pretty nice gear.  Not too long ago, folks were willing to pay 8k for a tae ew tunic.  Blood farmers could ask a price of 2k per blood.  At that price, my cost to make the tunic, taking the GM failure rate into consideration and the price of the other ingredients was about 6k, and I made a profit of about 2k.  The demand for tae ew gear has dropped significantly, reflecting many factors.  I can sell tunics for about 4k now.  If you want to price blood at 2k, I am priced out of your market.  I won’t complain about your price, but I won’t buy, either.  Are you willing to farm tae ew blood at 1k each?  Well, that’s your choice, and reflects the judgments you make about the value of your time and your other opportunities to turn your time into plat.  If you will sell for 1k, then I can make the tunics for an average price of 3500 pp, and so make a profit of 500 pp.  Its still worth my time to make tunics at that price, so, I’ll buy your blood at 1k.  And, for those following the tae ew market, you’ll see that it is now possible to buy blood for 1k.  There is now less profit for blood farmers and smiths, but a profit remains, nonetheless.  If demand for tae ew gear shrinks to the point where the time investment is too great to justify the return yielded by the price commanded by the finished products, then the farming and smithing will drop off.  <br>
<br>
Is anyone in the process guilty of “greed”?  Are the prices for the blood “fair”?  Are the prices the customers willing to pay for tunics “fair”?<br>
<br>
These value judgments are irrelevent.  A ranger will buy a tae ew tunic for the lowest price he can find, and no one should fault him for this.  If tae ew is too expensive relative to other comparable dropped or player made armor, he’ll buy something else.  <br>
<br>
A blood farmer will sell blood for as much as he can get, and will quit farming if the price gets too low.<br>
<br>
A smith will sell his tunic for as much as folks are willing to pay for it, and will buy supplies at the lowest price he can find.  If the profits get too slim, he’ll quit making that product.<br>
<br>
That’s just the way the world works, Norrath included.  Complaining about it is like complaining about the weather.<br>
<br>
Azurefox<br>
